[00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.680]   This is a KEL blog post from December 7, 2005 titled "Gartner's Death of the Database."
[00:00:05.680 --> 00:00:09.920]   Early in my career, I interviewed at Gartner for a job as an analyst. During the meetings,
[00:00:09.920 --> 00:00:14.320]   I met with Mike Broad, then head of research. Mike had made himself famous by declaring the
[00:00:14.320 --> 00:00:18.880]   death of IBM's SAA about two days after it was launched. I remember when we talked about
[00:00:18.880 --> 00:00:23.600]   research quality. "Do you know what great research is, Dave?" he asked. I can't remember exactly
[00:00:23.600 --> 00:00:27.680]   what I said, but I probably used words like "fair," "factual," and "customer-centric."
[00:00:28.400 --> 00:00:33.280]   "Dave, great research is research that sells." At the time, I think I saw little horns sprouting
[00:00:33.280 --> 00:00:37.440]   from his head as he said it, but today I know what he meant. He assumed research would be fair,
[00:00:37.440 --> 00:00:41.440]   factual, and customer-centric. But to be great, it needed more. It needed to have
[00:00:41.440 --> 00:00:45.600]   sizzle and controversy. It needed to make you think. I'm happy to report that the tradition
[00:00:45.600 --> 00:00:49.520]   of sizzle and controversy lives on today. While I didn't attend Gartner's recent
[00:00:49.520 --> 00:00:53.520]   symposium conference, I have heard a lot about a presentation by Mark Beyer and Donald Feinberg
[00:00:53.520 --> 00:00:58.160]   entitled "The Death of the Database." From what I've read of the session, here's the key point.
[00:00:58.160 --> 00:01:03.040]   Some types of data don't really need to be in databases, especially in an RFID world. In fact,
[00:01:03.040 --> 00:01:07.360]   this is a question I'd wondered about ever since I first started using databases in the 1980s.
[00:01:07.360 --> 00:01:11.440]   The inventory table is a model of a reality. Reality is what's in the warehouse,
[00:01:11.440 --> 00:01:15.840]   and for lots of reasons, e.g. error, theft, or damage, the reality in the model don't always
[00:01:15.840 --> 00:01:20.320]   match. Companies do a lot of work to minimize discrepancies between reality and the model.
[00:01:20.320 --> 00:01:23.840]   They take great pains to ensure that all additions and subtractions are correctly
[00:01:23.840 --> 00:01:28.080]   reflected in the database. And because they know that even painstaking processes won't guarantee
[00:01:28.080 --> 00:01:32.320]   synchronization, they periodically audit the inventory and update the database.
[00:01:32.320 --> 00:01:35.120]   You can even get philosophical in thinking about this problem.
[00:01:35.120 --> 00:01:39.040]   At Ingress, I always wondered about this epistemological question. If my record in the
[00:01:39.040 --> 00:01:43.760]   employee database were flagged terminated, which was more likely, database were flagged terminated,
[00:01:43.760 --> 00:01:48.640]   which was more likely, next, that there was an error in the database. Reality was right,
[00:01:48.640 --> 00:01:52.960]   and the model was wrong. Next, that I'd been fired and no one had actually gotten around to
[00:01:52.960 --> 00:01:57.280]   telling me. My guess was the world would increasingly find itself in the second case,
[00:01:57.280 --> 00:02:02.080]   when, in effect, does the model become reality. So, if the question you're asking is "What's
[00:02:02.080 --> 00:02:06.320]   in the warehouse right now?" then I agree that it's infinitely better to just go ask the warehouse
[00:02:06.320 --> 00:02:11.280]   via RFID. However, if the question is "What was in the warehouse last week?" or "How have
[00:02:11.280 --> 00:02:15.920]   inventory levels changed over time?" then you're back in the database business. And the Gartner
[00:02:15.920 --> 00:02:20.320]   guys both address and concede this example. I believe they're really arguing that real-time
[00:02:20.320 --> 00:02:25.360]   databases about physical objects need not exist in an RFID world. I think it's a great point.
[00:02:25.360 --> 00:02:28.800]   But what happens in this world is not the death of databases, but the replacement of
[00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:32.960]   databases with data warehouses. The former typically focus on the present and the latter
[00:02:32.960 --> 00:02:38.240]   on the past. I'm almost giddy that, per this blog, Feinberg and Beyer also apparently said,
[00:02:38.240 --> 00:02:42.000]   "Next, only 20% of the data that's stored will be structured anyway. Next,
[00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:47.200]   that XML and XQuery will be useful for accessing the other 80%. Next, that searching unstructured
[00:02:47.200 --> 00:02:51.040]   information will be important. Since the blog doesn't double-quote them, I can't be sure they
[00:02:51.040 --> 00:02:56.320]   said SQL will take a backseat to XQuery, but one can dream. Either way, this is not business,
[00:02:56.320 --> 00:03:00.720]   as usual for Gartner who, just a few years ago, answered most database inquiries with
[00:03:00.720 --> 00:03:06.720]   "Take DB2, Oracle, or SQL" or "L server and call me in the morning." BI was not spared in
[00:03:06.720 --> 00:03:11.440]   the presentation, with the analysts arguing that it wasn't an application anymore and would be
[00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:16.800]   embedded into operational applications. I both agree and disagree. In my nearly 10 years in
[00:03:16.800 --> 00:03:23.040]   BI, I came to believe there were three segments. Next, contextual BI. The use of BI to produce
[00:03:23.040 --> 00:03:27.840]   standard reports that enable everyone to develop a common understanding of what's normal and how
[00:03:27.840 --> 00:03:33.120]   things work around here. This is the most popular use of BI and it's basically ignored by the market.
[00:03:33.120 --> 00:03:39.680]   Next, operational BI. The embedding of intelligence into applications. What's better, a data mining
[00:03:39.680 --> 00:03:44.640]   tool that produces a list of the top 50 leads or a telemarketing application that sorts the leads
[00:03:44.640 --> 00:03:48.640]   automatically by sales value and presents them to the telemarketers in that order.
[00:03:48.640 --> 00:03:53.200]   Operational applications will get smarter over time and this will end.
[00:03:53.200 --> 00:03:58.320]   Trued on the traditional BI market. Next, analytical BI. This is heavy lifting with
[00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:03.120]   stats tools and data mining. This will remain the domain of the lab coat crowd and will remain an
[00:04:03.120 --> 00:04:07.840]   important segment of the market. So I'm happy to see that Gartner is producing some thought-provoking
[00:04:07.840 --> 00:04:12.800]   database research, mixing it up, and generating some controversy. But, to paraphrase Twain,
[00:04:12.800 --> 00:04:16.720]   I do think the rumors of the database's death have been at least somewhat exaggerated.
[00:04:16.720 --> 00:04:22.800]   Author's notes, 111706. Since the original posting, I have learned the following things via
[00:04:22.800 --> 00:04:27.200]   emails from Mark Beyer and Donald Feinberg of Gartner. Next, the presentation was done by
[00:04:27.200 --> 00:04:32.160]   Donald Feinberg and Mark Beyer, not Ted Friedman, as I had originally said. Ted and Daniel Schaller
[00:04:32.160 --> 00:04:37.200]   co-contributors to the materials. Apologies for the mistake. Next, Mark Beyer says they said that
[00:04:37.200 --> 00:04:42.800]   xQary would challenge and eventually overwhelm SQL. Next, Donald Feinberg says that xQary wouldn't
[00:04:42.800 --> 00:04:47.280]   replace SQL, but the two would work together. I don't take the last two bullets as inconsistent,
[00:04:47.280 --> 00:04:51.520]   but interpret them as meaning that they believe xQuery will gradually increase in uptake over time,
[00:04:51.520 --> 00:04:56.320]   be believe xQary will gradually increase in uptake over time, be better than SQL,
[00:04:56.320 --> 00:04:59.920]   jing here, and that two will need to live together for a long time.
