[00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.320]   This is a Kell blog post from December 20, 2005 titled "Unlikely Foes Custom Publishing
[00:00:05.320 --> 00:00:06.640]   and Enterprise Search."
[00:00:06.640 --> 00:00:08.680]   Here's a mind-expanding idea.
[00:00:08.680 --> 00:00:11.960]   What if the reason you couldn't find something was because it didn't exist?
[00:00:11.960 --> 00:00:15.360]   This occurred to me the other day when speaking with a friend who works in a big company's
[00:00:15.360 --> 00:00:16.580]   market intelligence department.
[00:00:16.580 --> 00:00:19.240]   He faces the same problem every marketing team does.
[00:00:19.240 --> 00:00:20.920]   The lament goes something like this.
[00:00:20.920 --> 00:00:24.800]   Next, their customer, the sales department, doesn't appreciate their work.
[00:00:24.800 --> 00:00:29.200]   Next, they have very smart analysts who write lots of brilliant documents but nobody reads
[00:00:29.200 --> 00:00:30.320]   them next.
[00:00:30.320 --> 00:00:33.600]   Nobody reads them, he supposed, because they can't find them.
[00:00:33.600 --> 00:00:37.280]   Since this sounded like a technology problem, they ran off to IT to solve it.
[00:00:37.280 --> 00:00:38.280]   The solution?
[00:00:38.280 --> 00:00:40.200]   Deploy a new enterprise search engine.
[00:00:40.200 --> 00:00:43.700]   If the existing search engine wasn't working, then something had to be wrong with it, so
[00:00:43.700 --> 00:00:44.900]   get a new one.
[00:00:44.900 --> 00:00:47.960]   If this dime isn't good at turning screws, then get a new dime.
[00:00:47.960 --> 00:00:50.160]   Don't consider the possibility of a screwdriver.
[00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:54.120]   In thinking about this problem, and in applying my years of marketing management experience,
[00:00:54.120 --> 00:00:55.480]   I had a deep thought.
[00:00:55.480 --> 00:00:59.060]   The reason sales couldn't find the desired information had nothing to do with the relative
[00:00:59.060 --> 00:01:01.740]   efficiency of various tech search algorithms.
[00:01:01.740 --> 00:01:02.740]   It was simple.
[00:01:02.740 --> 00:01:06.580]   The document any given salesperson actually wanted simply didn't exist.
[00:01:06.580 --> 00:01:10.840]   Marketing departments typically produce documents like Next, Product Data Sheet Next, Product
[00:01:10.840 --> 00:01:17.580]   Technical Overview, Next, Industry Applications Sheet, EDG, Telecom Applications Sheet, EDG,
[00:01:17.580 --> 00:01:22.860]   Telecom Applications, Next, Customer Case Study, Next, Problem Solutions Sheet, EG, Improving
[00:01:22.860 --> 00:01:28.180]   Customer Retention, Next, Problem White Paper, Next, Competitor Business Overview Next,
[00:01:28.180 --> 00:01:31.140]   Competitor Technical Overview Next, Competitor Selling Strategies.
[00:01:31.140 --> 00:01:33.460]   That's not what a salesperson wants.
[00:01:33.460 --> 00:01:36.660]   Salespeople, as they say, are both coin-operated and me-centric.
[00:01:36.660 --> 00:01:40.860]   They don't want to read 15 different documents and extract the relevant bits for any given
[00:01:40.860 --> 00:01:41.860]   situation.
[00:01:41.860 --> 00:01:45.660]   They want a document that contains all the information, and only the information.
[00:01:45.660 --> 00:01:47.460]   They need for that situation.
[00:01:47.460 --> 00:01:49.700]   Put concretely, they need for that situation.
[00:01:49.700 --> 00:01:53.380]   Next, Competitor Business Overviews for the Competitors in a Given Deal.
[00:01:53.380 --> 00:01:57.100]   Next, the most powerfully differentiating features given both the problem the customer
[00:01:57.100 --> 00:02:00.140]   is facing and the competitors under evaluation.
[00:02:00.140 --> 00:02:02.260]   Next, Customer References.
[00:02:02.260 --> 00:02:06.380]   Not in general, but specific to the industry, problem, and ideally competitor set for the
[00:02:06.380 --> 00:02:07.380]   deal.
[00:02:07.380 --> 00:02:10.460]   Next, Selling Strategies Relevant to the Situation at Hand.
[00:02:10.460 --> 00:02:13.060]   Next, Supplemental Technical Information.
[00:02:13.060 --> 00:02:15.980]   Again, relevant to the situation at hand.
[00:02:15.980 --> 00:02:17.260]   This document doesn't exist.
[00:02:17.260 --> 00:02:18.340]   It can't exist.
[00:02:18.340 --> 00:02:19.740]   There are too many combinations.
[00:02:19.740 --> 00:02:24.580]   Well, I ask, if a document doesn't exist, then can a search engine help you find it?
[00:02:24.580 --> 00:02:25.580]   No way.
[00:02:25.580 --> 00:02:29.060]   This is a custom publishing problem dressed in enterprise search clothing.
[00:02:29.060 --> 00:02:33.060]   Instead of assuming the desired document exists and then framing the exercise as a quixotic
[00:02:33.060 --> 00:02:36.860]   search quest, assume the desired document doesn't exist and provide a system to help
[00:02:36.860 --> 00:02:38.220]   someone build it.
[00:02:38.220 --> 00:02:41.620]   Our customers in the publishing industry have already figured this out.
[00:02:41.620 --> 00:02:45.500]   One customer is building a custom publishing system that lets professors build custom course
[00:02:45.500 --> 00:02:47.500]   readers on top of marked logic.
[00:02:47.500 --> 00:02:51.060]   Instead of searching for the perfect course text, you can build the one you want.
[00:02:51.060 --> 00:02:55.780]   But we've yet to see a publishing function of an enterprise, such as marketing or tech
[00:02:55.780 --> 00:02:57.020]   department, make the same leap.
[00:02:57.020 --> 00:02:58.020]   Hopefully they will.
[00:02:58.020 --> 00:03:01.780]   It's certainly not obvious to see that custom publishing and search are indeed unlikely
[00:03:01.780 --> 00:03:02.780]   foes.
[00:03:02.780 --> 00:03:05.980]   But once you realize it, you never see things quite the same way again.
