[00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.080]   This is a KEL blog post from March 3, 2006 titled "Enterprise Search, Nascent, or Just Small."
[00:00:06.080 --> 00:00:10.720]   Oracle had some PR coverage this week for their launch of Oracle Secure Enterprise Search 10 EGG,
[00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:14.800]   their new enterprise search solution. Oracle can now compete not only with traditional
[00:00:14.800 --> 00:00:19.280]   enterprise search vendors such as Vautonomy and FAST, but also with fellow database vendors who
[00:00:19.280 --> 00:00:24.320]   already have enterprise search solutions such as IBM Ondifind and Microsoft Index Server.
[00:00:24.320 --> 00:00:27.840]   Here is a Red Herring article and also a TechWorld article that cover the story.
[00:00:28.400 --> 00:00:32.560]   Rather than my standard schtick on the limitations of enterprise search engines as platforms for
[00:00:32.560 --> 00:00:36.880]   building content applications, I thought I'd instead call out the Red Herring for buying the
[00:00:36.880 --> 00:00:42.160]   message that enterprise search is somehow a new market. Enterprise search isn't new. It is,
[00:00:42.160 --> 00:00:46.480]   however, small. Not confusing the two is important. And understanding why enterprise
[00:00:46.480 --> 00:00:50.240]   search is small, despite not being new, is probably most important of all.
[00:00:50.240 --> 00:00:54.320]   Here's what the Herring said, "Nascent enterprise search is not new."
[00:00:54.320 --> 00:00:59.120]   Next, Verity was founded in 1988. See here for an interesting early paper.
[00:00:59.120 --> 00:01:03.760]   Next, Autonomy was founded in 1996, based on work dating to 1990.
[00:01:03.760 --> 00:01:09.840]   Enterprise search is, however, small. Next, a big enterprise search vendor does 30M to 50M
[00:01:09.840 --> 00:01:15.440]   per quarter in revenue. Next, a big BI vendor does 300M per quarter in revenue.
[00:01:15.440 --> 00:01:20.400]   Next, a big database vendor does 3B+ per quarter. Yes, these are order of magnitude
[00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:24.480]   numbers, which in Oracle's case include non-database revenues, but the point stands.
[00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:31.920]   So why? Despite similar age to BIEG, BOBJ founded in 1990, and despite being only about 10 years
[00:01:31.920 --> 00:01:38.320]   younger than RDBMS, EG, or CL founded in 1978, is enterprise search 1/1 that, the size of the BI
[00:01:38.320 --> 00:01:42.800]   market, and 1/100th the size of the database market? Here's my answer.
[00:01:42.800 --> 00:01:47.040]   Next, content has always been the third layer on the corporate IT Maslow hierarchy.
[00:01:47.600 --> 00:01:52.720]   Back office systems are food, front office systems are shelter, content documents are love and
[00:01:52.720 --> 00:01:57.200]   belonging. This isn't the fault of enterprise search vendors, and I do expect it to change in
[00:01:57.200 --> 00:02:03.200]   the future as the lower-level needs are increasingly well met. Next, enterprise search products stink.
[00:02:03.200 --> 00:02:08.000]   Users are not happy with them. While the technology, per se, works, it doesn't actually help people
[00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:13.200]   find anything. Personal example, I can't remember if I ever successfully found anything I needed on
[00:02:13.200 --> 00:02:18.640]   the business objects interter, a net using our enterprise search engine. Next, many enterprise
[00:02:18.640 --> 00:02:22.640]   search problems aren't. When you think about it, enterprise search is predicated on the existence
[00:02:22.640 --> 00:02:26.560]   of the thing for which you are searching. In reality, I think companies should invest in
[00:02:26.560 --> 00:02:30.160]   custom publishing systems so people can build the document they need instead of searching
[00:02:30.160 --> 00:02:33.200]   in vain for something that isn't there. See this post for more.
[00:02:33.200 --> 00:02:37.760]   Next, enterprise search is a feature, not a market. That's why a lot of enterprise search
[00:02:37.760 --> 00:02:42.640]   business is embedded. For example, at business objects, we needed search in our portal and we
[00:02:42.640 --> 00:02:47.360]   licensed it from autonomy. I'm not sure it helped out customers find anything either, but it was a
[00:02:47.360 --> 00:02:52.480]   required checkbox item. This reality is why smart search vendors are trying to build applications
[00:02:52.480 --> 00:02:57.280]   that solve search-oriented problems as opposed to try and push more and more search boxes.
[00:02:57.280 --> 00:03:01.120]   But that's a packaged application approach, which makes for better sales and marketing,
[00:03:01.120 --> 00:03:05.840]   but which is wrong technologically. Overall, what's needed is an application platform designed
[00:03:05.840 --> 00:03:10.720]   specifically for content-oriented applications. That market is indeed nascent today, but I think
[00:03:10.720 --> 00:03:15.840]   in the future it will be anything but small. This audio version was created by Grant Duncan and AI
[00:03:15.840 --> 00:03:17.840]   with permission from Dave.
