[00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.440]   This is a Kellblad post from March 13, 2006 titled "Flying Airplanes or Documents."
[00:00:05.440 --> 00:00:09.840]   I met a few months back with one of our customers in aviation to discuss how Marc Logic could help
[00:00:09.840 --> 00:00:14.640]   his airline with flight documentation. During the meeting, I learned that flight documentation is
[00:00:14.640 --> 00:00:19.040]   yet another example of a custom publishing system, but one that's about as mission-critical as they
[00:00:19.040 --> 00:00:25.840]   come. Why? Next, each airline has its own flight operating manuals, i.e., the airline's documentation
[00:00:25.840 --> 00:00:31.200]   policies. Next, each airframe manufacturer provides its own documentation, i.e., the dock
[00:00:31.200 --> 00:00:35.920]   for the airplane. Next, these documents are subject to a stream of changes and updates
[00:00:35.920 --> 00:00:40.880]   that one would expect for a complex product in a changing industry. Next, these documents are also
[00:00:40.880 --> 00:00:47.920]   specific to a given airplane, YATA TATA tail number. As it turns out, not all 737s or A320s are
[00:00:47.920 --> 00:00:52.240]   identical. There are variations in manufacturing that require each plane to have its own custom
[00:00:52.240 --> 00:00:56.480]   dock. This problem is known as "effectivity" in the business because you need to know that a
[00:00:56.480 --> 00:01:02.560]   specific procedure is only effective to tail number, ours 1523 that contain a specific assembly.
[00:01:02.560 --> 00:01:06.880]   Next, overlaid against this is a stream of notices and regulatory updates that come from
[00:01:06.880 --> 00:01:11.040]   the government. So finding out what to do when you strike a bird isn't as simple as turning to page
[00:01:11.040 --> 00:01:16.240]   57 in a single book. You can think of it as fine-grained, "get me the paragraph, not the chapter,"
[00:01:16.240 --> 00:01:21.040]   context-specific, "I am on takeoff, not approach," search across the above silos of content. In
[00:01:21.040 --> 00:01:25.600]   reality, I'm told that flight crews literally have three books open and their fingers jammed in each
[00:01:25.600 --> 00:01:30.240]   of them to cross-reference the procedures that should be followed in a given S. Ituation. As
[00:01:30.240 --> 00:01:33.920]   a frequent flyer, I'm happy that we're working with this customer to prototype and build better
[00:01:33.920 --> 00:01:37.920]   ways to get flight crews the information they need. I remember at one point during the meeting,
[00:01:37.920 --> 00:01:42.400]   the customer said, "We don't fly airplanes, we fly documents. If the documents aren't correct,
[00:01:42.400 --> 00:01:46.560]   the planes don't leave the ground." I chalked it up to heat of the moment hyperbole until I read
[00:01:46.560 --> 00:01:51.280]   this blog post on the content wrangler this morning. The post points to this underlying article from
[00:01:51.280 --> 00:01:55.760]   which I quote, "The Transport Canada inspectors revoked JetSCO's operating certificate when they
[00:01:55.760 --> 00:02:00.640]   discovered certain incomplete descriptions in the JetSCO manuals. This forced JetSCO to fly at lower
[00:02:00.640 --> 00:02:05.600]   altitudes, which in turn increased fuel consumption and, by mid-March, ultimately put the airline out
[00:02:05.600 --> 00:02:10.880]   of business. Maybe airlines really do fly documents and not airplanes. Or, better put, without the
[00:02:10.880 --> 00:02:15.920]   right documents, the airplanes don't fly." This audio version was created by Grant Duncan and AI,
