[00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.640]   This is a kell blog post from March 20, 2006, titled "MarkLogic, DBMS, or Search Engine."
[00:00:06.640 --> 00:00:10.080]   At MarkLogic Corporation, we make an XML server.
[00:00:10.080 --> 00:00:15.280]   The product's name is, ever so subtly, MarkLogic Server, or just MarkLogic for short.
[00:00:15.280 --> 00:00:18.960]   This post provides some Q&A that helps you understand how we think about,
[00:00:18.960 --> 00:00:21.920]   or in marketing speak, position, or product.
[00:00:21.920 --> 00:00:23.840]   What is an XML server?
[00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:29.120]   A special-purpose database management system, DBMS, built for handling XML content.
[00:00:29.120 --> 00:00:32.480]   MarkLogic Server is, in fact, a special case of this category,
[00:00:32.480 --> 00:00:35.200]   because it is architected to handle markup in general.
[00:00:35.200 --> 00:00:38.320]   We have implemented XML because it's the obvious choice today,
[00:00:38.320 --> 00:00:40.320]   but we're another markup language to take off,
[00:00:40.320 --> 00:00:43.440]   my technical team tells me it would not be hard to transition to it.
[00:00:43.440 --> 00:00:44.800]   What do you mean by content?
[00:00:44.800 --> 00:00:46.240]   In short, anything but data.
[00:00:46.240 --> 00:00:50.000]   That is, anything that isn't exclusively the numerical and short text fields,
[00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:54.000]   e.g., name, birthday, social security number, address, phone, salary,
[00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:58.000]   that relational and other prior-generation DBMSs were designed to accommodate.
[00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:00.640]   At MarkLogic, we usually take content to mean documents,
[00:01:00.640 --> 00:01:03.440]   though over time I suspect we will move to a broader definition
[00:01:03.440 --> 00:01:06.640]   as more and more multimedia content gets markup added to it.
[00:01:06.640 --> 00:01:08.720]   Is MarkLogic really a DBMS?
[00:01:08.720 --> 00:01:09.440]   Yes.
[00:01:09.440 --> 00:01:13.840]   If you think of an RDBMS as server where SQL goes in and tables come back,
[00:01:13.840 --> 00:01:18.560]   then you can think of MarkLogic in the exact same way xQuery goes in and XML comes back.
[00:01:18.560 --> 00:01:23.040]   That is, if you view a DBMS as a system that processes a query language,
[00:01:23.040 --> 00:01:25.200]   then MarkLogic is very much a DBMS.
[00:01:25.840 --> 00:01:29.840]   If you take a more internal viewpoint and say a DBMS is something that provides storage,
[00:01:29.840 --> 00:01:32.720]   transactions, concurrency, and backup and recovery,
[00:01:32.720 --> 00:01:35.040]   then MarkLogic qualifies as a DBMS as well.
[00:01:35.040 --> 00:01:40.400]   For example, MarkLogic supports concurrency, ACID transactions, backup and recovery,
[00:01:40.400 --> 00:01:44.080]   and read-consistent snapshots, among other core DBMS features.
[00:01:44.080 --> 00:01:47.360]   As an aside, I had this question myself when I joined MarkLogic.
[00:01:47.360 --> 00:01:51.040]   So on my third day, I asked John Pilot, formerly VP of Software Engineering
[00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:55.200]   for Server Technologies at Oracle and now a part-time technology strategist at MarkLogic
[00:01:55.200 --> 00:01:57.840]   if MarkLogic was indeed a real DBMS.
[00:01:57.840 --> 00:02:00.640]   His three-word answer, typical of his pithy style,
[00:02:00.640 --> 00:02:03.360]   was "bits on iron," which I very much took for yes.
[00:02:03.360 --> 00:02:05.680]   Is MarkLogic really a search engine?
[00:02:05.680 --> 00:02:11.120]   Since MarkLogic architect and company founder Christopher Lindblad, PhD, is a search guy,
[00:02:11.120 --> 00:02:14.400]   there is most certainly a lot of search engine technology in MarkLogic.
[00:02:14.400 --> 00:02:18.160]   Specifically, the product uses search engine style indexing,
[00:02:18.160 --> 00:02:22.720]   but does so at a sub-document level, and search engine-style clustering for scalability.
[00:02:23.280 --> 00:02:26.480]   So, while I would not say that MarkLogic is really a search engine,
[00:02:26.480 --> 00:02:29.280]   I would say that it uses a lot of search engine technology,
[00:02:29.280 --> 00:02:31.760]   which is one of the things that makes MarkLogic unique.
[00:02:31.760 --> 00:02:33.920]   What's the best metaphor for MarkLogic?
[00:02:33.920 --> 00:02:37.680]   I think of MarkLogic as a car that looks like a DBMS on the outside,
[00:02:37.680 --> 00:02:41.040]   but when you open up the hood, you find a motor that looks more like a search engine
[00:02:41.040 --> 00:02:42.720]   than a traditional DBMS.
[00:02:42.720 --> 00:02:46.320]   If MarkLogic is really a DBMS, then why are you drone on about search,
[00:02:46.320 --> 00:02:49.360]   simply because MarkLogic competes with search engines today?
[00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:53.040]   Most customers know that our DBMSs do not handle content well,
[00:02:53.040 --> 00:02:55.760]   sometimes we find customers who have been struggling for 18 months
[00:02:55.760 --> 00:02:58.160]   trying to build content applications on Oracle,
[00:02:58.160 --> 00:03:01.600]   but usually we find people who don't bother to try using an RDBMS
[00:03:01.600 --> 00:03:03.440]   and just leave content on the file system,
[00:03:03.440 --> 00:03:08.720]   or who do the spiritual DBMS equivalent of not trying and simply stuff the content into BLOBs
[00:03:08.720 --> 00:03:10.800]   and then use a search engine to index it,
[00:03:10.800 --> 00:03:14.480]   but either way, they hope to get query functionality from a search engine which,
[00:03:14.480 --> 00:03:17.360]   next, almost certainly was never designed to handle XML.
[00:03:17.360 --> 00:03:20.080]   I'll do an upcoming post on how search engines view XML
[00:03:20.080 --> 00:03:22.160]   as that stuff that gets in the way of the text.
[00:03:22.160 --> 00:03:24.960]   Next, from a DBMS viewpoint is a one-trick pony,
[00:03:24.960 --> 00:03:27.360]   i.e. the one query the search engine runs is,
[00:03:27.360 --> 00:03:30.320]   "Return a list of links to documents containing word or phrase."
[00:03:30.320 --> 00:03:32.720]   Next requires you to do a lot of content processing
[00:03:32.720 --> 00:03:35.600]   that should have been done in XQuery and processed by the server instead
[00:03:35.600 --> 00:03:37.200]   in Java DOM on a middle tier.
[00:03:37.200 --> 00:03:40.080]   We show these people a better way to build content applications.
[00:03:40.080 --> 00:03:42.480]   So the net answer to this question is that,
[00:03:42.480 --> 00:03:45.440]   since no traditional DBMS is up for the job,
[00:03:45.440 --> 00:03:49.280]   most customers turn to search engines to try and solve a DBMS problem,
[00:03:49.280 --> 00:03:51.040]   until they find us, that is.
